<center>
<h3><font color="blue">Chapter 11</font></h3>
<h1>Synchronization Mechanisms over Broadband Networks</h1>
</center>
<hr size=3>

<h2>
<image src="gr_ball.gif"> Synchronization Interval Unit (SIU) <br></h2>
<h3>
<ul>
  <image src="yellow.gif"> Smallest unit for maintaining synchronization <br>
  <image src="yellow.gif"> SIU for a video object can be 1/30th of a second. <br>
  <image src="yellow.gif"> SIU for an image or text can be the entire object. <br>
</ul>
</h3>

<h2>
<image src="gr_ball.gif"> Deadline-Based Scheduling for Synchronization<br>
</h2>
<h3>
<ul>
   <img src="yellow.gif"> SIU should be pre-scheduled because of network delay :
   <i>control time</i> <br>
   <img src="yellow.gif"> Control time depends on size,delay and channel capacity 
   requirement of a representative data object. <br>
   <img src="yellow.gif"> If the QOP parameters can not meet, the connection can
   be denied or use partial dropping. <br>
</ul>
<h3>

<h2>
<image src="gr_ball.gif"> Feedback Techniques for Synchronization <br> </h2>
<h3>
<ul>
   <img src="yellow.gif"> Multimedia server must keep some data in the buffer.<br>
   <img src="yellow.gif"> Client send light-weighted message called <i>feedback
   unit</i> periodically to server. <br>
   <img src="yellow.gif"> Server use feedback unit to estimate a better actual
   playback rate. <br>
   <img src="yellow.gif"> Re-synchronization policies are 
   <p>
   <center>
   <table border=5 cellpadding=5>
   <tr>
   <td><b>conservative</b>
   <td>Server reacts only when play-out of different streams is guaranteed to be
   asynchronous.
   </tr>
   <tr>
   <td><b>aggressive</b>
   <td>Server reacts as soon as there is even a slight chance that playback
   is asynchronous.
   </tr>
   <tr>
   <td><b>probabilistic</b>
   <td>Server reacts on the average
   </tr>
   </table>
   <p>

</ul>
<h3>


